how to delete or rename volumn

Yes. Docker volumes can be deleted, but Docker does not have a direct docker volume rename command.

1. Delete a volume

First, see your volumes:

docker volume ls

Your volume is:

f92e831d3904b4027691fdbf533a2b6d7aa4a1b90e63074d76f5ca803b8c4c50

Remove it:

docker volume rm f92e831d3904b4027691fdbf533a2b6d7aa4a1b90e63074d76f5ca803b8c4c50

⚠️ Be careful: This permanently deletes the data stored in the volume.

If the volume is being used by a container, Docker will give you an error. You need to stop and remove the container first:

docker stop jenkins
docker rm jenkins

Then:

docker volume rm f92e831d3904b4027691fdbf533a2b6d7aa4a1b90e63074d76f5ca803b8c4c50
2. Rename a volume

Docker doesn't have:

docker volume rename

Instead, you can create a new volume and copy the data.

For example, rename your random volume to:

jenkins_home
Step 1: Create the new volume
docker volume create jenkins_home
Step 2: Copy the data

You can use a temporary Ubuntu container:

docker run --rm \
  -v f92e831d3904b4027691fdbf533a2b6d7aa4a1b90e63074d76f5ca803b8c4c50:/from \
  -v jenkins_home:/to \
  ubuntu \
  bash -c "cp -a /from/. /to/"

The result is:

Old volume
f92e831d3904...
       │
       │ copy data
       ▼
New volume
jenkins_home
Step 3: Verify
docker volume ls

You should see both:

f92e831d3904...
jenkins_home
Step 4: Use the new volume with Jenkins

If you remove and recreate your Jenkins container:

docker run -d \
  --name jenkins \
  -p 8070:8080 \
  -p 50000:50000 \
  -v jenkins_home:/var/jenkins_home \
  jenkins/jenkins:lts

Jenkins will now use:

jenkins_home

instead of the long random volume name.

Step 5: Delete the old volume

Only after you confirm that Jenkins works correctly with the new volume:

docker volume rm f92e831d3904b4027691fdbf533a2b6d7aa4a1b90e63074d76f5ca803b8c4c50

My recommendation: Since your volume name looks like a randomly generated name, I would back it up first, copy it to jenkins_home, verify Jenkins, and only then delete the old volume. This gives you a safe recovery path if something goes wrong.

can i use the same container jenkins with different volumn when i use run

Yes, but not with the same container. docker run always creates a new container. You cannot use docker run to change the volume attached to an existing container.

Think of it like this:

Container: jenkins
    │
    └── Volume: old_volume

If you want the same Jenkins container to use a different volume, you have two options.

Option 1: Create a new container with the new volume

First stop and remove the old container:

docker stop jenkins
docker rm jenkins

Then create a new container with the same name but a different volume:

docker run -d \
  --name jenkins \
  -p 8070:8080 \
  -p 50000:50000 \
  -v jenkins_home:/var/jenkins_home \
  jenkins/jenkins:lts

The container is new, but you reuse the name jenkins.

Old:
jenkins container
      ↓
old_volume

Remove container
      ↓

New:
jenkins container
      ↓
jenkins_home

Your Jenkins data is preserved if you copied the old volume data into jenkins_home.

Option 2: Use the old container again

If you simply do:

docker start jenkins

Docker will use the same volume configuration that was defined when the container was created.

You cannot do this:

docker start jenkins -v new_volume:/var/jenkins_home

docker start does not let you change volume mounts.

The key difference
docker run

➡️ Creates a new container.

docker start

➡️ Starts an existing container with its original configuration.

So if you want to switch from:

old_volume

to:

jenkins_home

the normal approach is:

docker stop jenkins
docker rm jenkins

docker run -d \
  --name jenkins \
  -p 8070:8080 \
  -p 50000:50000 \
  -v jenkins_home:/var/jenkins_home \
  jenkins/jenkins:lts

The container is disposable, while the volume holds your persistent Jenkins data. This separation is one of the main advantages of Docker.
